<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="757" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6840318" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6840318" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6840318/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="757" targetBox="[101,690,2607,3020]" targetPageId="29">
<paragraph blockId="29.[714,1307,2601,3024]" pageId="29" pageNumber="757">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[714,891,2744,2790]" pageId="29" pageNumber="757">Distribution.</emphasis>
N &amp; WC Borneo, in Sabah and Sarawak (Malaysia) and NW Kalimantan, (Indonesia).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="757" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[714,1307,2601,3024]" lastBlockId="29.[104,1307,3031,3459]" pageId="29" pageNumber="757">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[715,995,2875,2908]" pageId="29" pageNumber="757">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 231-244 mm, tail 236-251 mm; weight ¢.370 g. Dorsum of the Kinabalu Squirrel is gray black, with reddish speckling on face and legs. Venter is dark reddish, sometimes with a mid-ventral dark line. It has short lateral stripes that are white over black. Tail is black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="757" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[104,1307,3031,3459]" pageId="29" pageNumber="757">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[105,215,3110,3143]" pageId="29" pageNumber="757">Habitat.</emphasis>
Montane oak (Quercus, Fagaceae), lower cloud forests and fringe agricultural lands. The Kinabalu Squirrel occurs in the mountains of north-western part ofisland of Borneo,at elevations of ¢.300-1800 m on Mount Kinabalu (Sabah, Malaysia).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
